Several small improvements, like:
- timestamp of tasks;
- heartbeat of workers;
- smaller params names, like `show_params` to `params`;
- negate flag in tasks and workers, to negate the result of a search by pattern.

This modification attempts to solve the issue #58 by including the signals module within \__init\__.py

Now to use a Flask-User signal, simply import it from the `flask.ext.user` namespace:

    from flask.ext.user import user_logged_in, user_logged_out

    @user_logged_in.connect_via(app)
    def logged_in(sender, user, **extra):
        sender.logger.info("USER LOGGED IN")

Recently I have had a lot of trouble with the impyla HiveServer2 database connection (primarily in Python 3), whereby the thrift transport would for some reason hang for long periods. This was especially pronounced after you cancelled a long running query. Just in case it is relevant, I am connecting to Hive 0.13.

This PR is the result of me attempting to find a quick fix, and after several attempts, the greatest stability was achieved by using Apache `thrift` everywhere instead of `thriftpy`, which had several weird issues regarding session handles if connections were terminated. The connection issues have not entirely disappeared, but they seem a lot better now.

As part of this search for a fix, I updated the thrift bindings using thrift 0.10.0.

As it is, this PR is not ready to merge, but before I went to the effort of cleaning it up, I wanted to check whether this is something that you would be interested in.

@wesm

@danfrankj You might be interested in confirming the increased stability I report here.

@emmett9001 Sorry this took so long, but here is the work I've done to add support for lz4. It requires [lz4 Bindings for Python](https://pypi.python.org/pypi/lz4). The methods [encode_lz4_old_kafka](https://github.com/Parsely/pykafka/compare/master...sghaskell:feature/lz4-support?expand=1#diff-be2d15aff9900ab3baca0523701a468eR213) and [decode_lz4_old_kafka](https://github.com/Parsely/pykafka/compare/master...sghaskell:feature/lz4-support?expand=1#diff-be2d15aff9900ab3baca0523701a468eR244) have been borrowed from [kafka-python codec.py](https://github.com/dpkp/kafka-python/blob/a00f9ead161e8b05ac953b460950e42fa0e0b7d6/kafka/codec.py). They exist to work around the bug I discuss [here](https://github.com/Parsely/pykafka/issues/709#issuecomment-324156080). In order to compress without error I had to set [block_mode=1](https://github.com/Parsely/pykafka/compare/master...sghaskell:feature/lz4-support?expand=1#diff-be2d15aff9900ab3baca0523701a468eR192) for [independent blockmode](http://python-lz4.readthedocs.io/en/latest/lz4.frame.html?highlight=block_mode#lz4.frame.compress). 

There is little to no error handling and I have not added any tests for the code.

I was able to successfully produce and consume lz4 v0 and v1 messages in my limited testing. Have a look and give it a try.

This was because returned dataset IDs in `v1beta2` turned `foo` into `s~foo` and sometimes this caused mismatches.

@pcostell Do we still need `foo` and `s~foo` to be considered "equal" in `v1beta3`?

I held off on removing the custom `_projects_equal`, which is used in `Key.__eq__`, `Batch.put`, `Batch.delete` and `Client.get_multi`. However, by making `_projects_equal` just check `project1 == project2` the system tests pass just fine. (This would fix #821)

